ce:section.ce:para:
It is important to evaluate the cytotoxicity of drug delivery vehicles in drug delivery systems. CDs have demonstrated successful application for fluorescence imaging in vitro and in vivo 
                     [40,43], taking advantage of their visible excitation and emission wavelengths, fluorescence brightness at the individual dot level, high photostability, and excellent biocompatibility. Previously, low cytotoxicity and intracellular multi-colored fluorescence of CDs from konjac flour internalized by HeLa cells have been studied in our reported work [6,45]. The HeLa cells retained viability higher than 80% even when treated with the CDs at a concentration of 150mg/mL, which demonstrates the low cytotoxicity of the CDs. Further, after 24h incubation with the CDs, the HeLa cells show blue, green and red colors when they were excited with 408, 488 and 549nm laser pulses, respectively (shown in Fig. 7
                     ). That is to say, the HeLa cells treated with CDs are multi-colored fluorescence. Obviously, the above mentioned results indicate that the CDs are suitable for long time cell imaging. As a control, the HeLa cells untreated with CDs did not show fluorescence at all.

As previously reported, the as-prepared CDs show strong, multi-color and tunable fluorescence as well as good dispersity in water and they can be used for cell imaging in Fig. 7 
                     [6,45]. Therefore the CDs were introduced into the hybrids to endow them strong and multi-colored fluorescence. Interestingly, CDs can cocatalyze the ROP of CL monomer and fasten the degradation of PCL macromolecule. Fluorescence properties of the obtained CDs@PCL hybrids were investigated at various excitations of 408nm, 488nm, and 549nm [6,40]. Obviously, CDs@PCL hybrids prepared by TA, CDs-cocatalyzed ring-opening polymerization retains the optical properties of CDs and the biocompatibility of PCL. These features are useful for future applications in exible optoelectronic devices [47] (Fig. 9
                     ).
